column26: Due to COVID19 I was part of a huge layoff, I have had a temp assignment earning less money for 11 days, and was then laid-off again due to COVID19 financial cut backs, then going to return to this assignment starting tomorrow May 4th, but only making enough to feed my family, only working 35 hours a week and earning $15 per hour. Just feel like I unfortunately will never be able to pay back my debt at this point with this world wide pandemic and the uncertainty. I feel life is just going to get harder, and now I need to save up for car repairs before I can even drive my car, which is a 2003 vehicle with over 200K miles on it. I have also been a single parent for four children and have taken on the responsibility for raising my family. I kept hoping life would get better, but then COVID19 happened, and I have been struggling. I am and have been so depressed about life and not being able to make any credit card and or loan payments, I just don't see any other answers but to unfortunately file bankruptcy at this point.

column26: My bad credit started to spiral out of control a few years ago when I had a boyfriend living with me and he was taking care of the finances. I had had accumulated several credit cards over a few years span and he came across them one day. Because we were both struggling to try to make ends meet he started to use my credit cards for our bills. Unbeannouncedt to me,  he also used the credit cards for his own spending habits as well.   I later found out tu as t he had a drug problem and would let his dealer pick out clothes, furniture. etc from my retail credit accounts and he would order the merchsndise and hide it from me.  He would then trade it to her fir drugster about 18 months of this I found out everything that was going on. I informed my parents oh, the boyfriend was kicked out of my apartment and I had to find a new apartment because I was being evicted at the time. I found a new apartment and my parents became my payee. I tried to start to pay my bills back however I found a dead-end every time I tried. The first being that I ended up having a medical condition being cancer that I had to have treatments for that cause me to only be able to work part-time. That's what stopped my minimum payment on my bills. After that I was able to gain full-time employment and then my garnishment started. It's been a struggle to try to stay above water since all of this has happened. By getting bankruptcies this will give me a fresh start again to be able to breathe and stay above water.

column26: I was in a relationship for 9 years and put myself last. I was not as responsible as I know I should have been, but I promise, I did try to do my best. I stayed when I shouldn't have and this is something that has haunted me forever. I recently went to apply for a used travel trailer, around $6k.. they told me I was denied and I wanted to cry on the spot. The sales lady January even text me the next day because she knew I was crushed. I want my life together. I need to be "normal". I want to feel like I have options. I need help. I don't know how to do this on my own and I am ashamed to sit in front of someone face to face and talk about my poor decision making.

column26: I have been living with my mother, who is now 80 years old, since my divorce in April of 2017, which left me with $32,761.78 in credit card debt. I joined National Debt Relief 9/3/2017 and have paid off $23,087.00 of that debt. In August of last year my mother was diagnosed with lymphoma. We had to sell her home in Baton Rouge and move to New Orleans for her treatment. I also had to quit my job in order to care for her while living at my brother's house. My brother had her Power of Attorney while she was undergoing chemotherapy, etc. My mother is doing much better now and thankfully, National Debt Relief was able to pause my payments. My mother and I have recently discovered that my brother has spent the proceeds from the sale of her house on the personal needs of himself and his family. Mom and I are devastated and he and his wife have asked us to move out.  We moved into a hotel last Sunday and found an apartment to move into for August 1st.  Luckily, I started a new job June 1st, but it is only $13/hour. I cannot believe life has come to this.
column27: I have been living with my mother, who is now 80 years old, since my divorce in April of 2017, which left me with $32,761.78 in credit card debt. I joined National Debt Relief 9/3/2017 and have paid off $23,087.00 of that debt. In August of last year my mother was diagnosed with lymphoma. We had to sell her home in Baton Rouge and move to New Orleans for her treatment. I also had to quit my job in order to care for her while living at my brother's house. My brother had her Power of Attorney while she was undergoing chemotherapy, etc. My mother is doing much better now and thankfully, National Debt Relief was able to pause my payments. My mother and I have recently discovered that my brother has spent the proceeds from the sale of her house on the personal needs of himself and his family. Mom and I are devastated and he and his wife have asked us to move out.  We moved into a hotel last Sunday and found an apartment to move into for August 1st.  Luckily, I started a new job June 1st, but it is only $13/hour. I cannot believe life has come to this.

column26: Judgments that I can't pay off. Civil cases. I am a single mother. One of the complaints that I was served recently is regarding a vehicle but I was told it was a loss to the bank (Denali FCU - Now Nuvision) and that they would not reposes it as it's not worth it to them to go after it. It's in another city where I had to leave it to fly home to Alaska from a domestic violence situation in an emergency with my (then) 2 year at the time (2 years ago). I called the bank immediately, told them where the vehicle was and have been in communication with them, but again, it was of no interest for them to retrieve their car. Now that a new company has bought the once Alaskan private bank, they are suing me for the loan and interest. Regarding the wages being garnished question,  I have none. Some back taxes that my tax return is paying to the IRS yearly from my employment.
